# Python For Loops
  [❮ Previous](python_while_loops.asp) [Next ❯](python_functions.asp)    
## Python For Loops
 A [for](ref_keyword_for.asp) loop is used for iterating over a sequence (that is either a list, a tuple, a dictionary, a set, or a string).
 This is less like the [for](ref_keyword_for.asp) keyword in other programming languages, and works more like an iterator method as found in other object-orientated programming languages.
 With the [for](ref_keyword_for.asp) loop we can execute a set of statements, once for each item in a list, tuple, set etc.
  
### Example[Get your own Python Server](/python/python_server.asp)
 Print each fruit in a fruit list:
   fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
for   x in fruits:
  print(x)   [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for)  The [for](ref_keyword_for.asp) loop does not require an indexing variable to set beforehand.
    
## Looping Through a String
 Even strings are iterable objects, they contain a sequence of characters:
  
### Example
 Loop through the letters in the word "banana":
   for x in "banana":
 print(x)   [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for_string)     
## The break Statement
 With the [break](ref_keyword_break.asp) statement we can stop the loop before it has looped through all the items:
  
### Example
 Exit the loop when x is "banana":
   fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
for x in fruits:
 print(x)  
 if x ==   "banana":
 break
   [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for_break)   
### Example
 Exit the loop when x is "banana", but this time the break comes before the print:
   fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
for x in fruits:
 if x ==   "banana":
 break
 print(x)   [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for_break2)       [REMOVE ADS](https://order.w3schools.com/plans)
   
## The continue Statement
 With the [continue](ref_keyword_continue.asp) statement we can stop the current iteration of the loop, and continue with the next:
  
### Example
 Do not print banana:
   fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
for x in fruits:
 if x ==   "banana":
 continue
 print(x)   [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for_continue)     
## The range() Function
 To loop through a set of code a specified number of times, we can use the [range()](ref_func_range.asp) function,
 The [range()](ref_func_range.asp) function returns a sequence of numbers, starting from 0 by default, and increments by 1 (by default), and ends at a specified number.
  
### Example
 Using the range() function:
   for x in range(6):
  print(x)   [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for_range)   Note that range(6) is not the values of 0 to 6, but the values 0 to 5.
    The [range()](ref_func_range.asp) function defaults to 0 as a starting value, however it is possible to specify the starting value by adding a parameter: range(2, 6), which means values from 2 to 6 (but not including 6):
  
### Example
 Using the start parameter:
   for x in range(2, 6):
  print(x)   [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for_range2)  The [range()](ref_func_range.asp) function defaults to increment the sequence by 1, however it is possible to specify the increment value by adding a third parameter: range(2, 30, **3**):
  
### Example
 Increment the sequence with 3 (default is 1):
   for x in range(2, 30, 3):
  print(x)   [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for_range3)     
## Else in For Loop
 The [else](ref_keyword_else.asp) keyword in a [for](ref_keyword_for.asp) loop specifies a block of code to be executed when the loop is finished:
  
### Example
 Print all numbers from 0 to 5, and print a message when the loop has ended:
   for x in range(6):
 print(x)
else:
 print("Finally finished!")  [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for_else)   **Note:** The [else](ref_keyword_else.asp) block will NOT be executed if the loop is stopped by a [break](ref_keyword_break.asp) statement.
   
### Example
 Break the loop when x is 3, and see what happens with the [else](ref_keyword_else.asp) block:
   for x in range(6):
 if x == 3: break
 print(x)
else:
 print("Finally finished!")  [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for_else_break)     
## Nested Loops
 A nested loop is a loop inside a loop.
 The "inner loop" will be executed one time for each iteration of the "outer loop":
  
### Example
 Print each adjective for every fruit:
   adj = ["red", "big", "tasty"]
fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
  
for x in adj:
 for y in fruits:
 print(x, y)  [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for_nested)     
## The pass Statement
 [for](ref_keyword_for.asp) loops cannot be empty, but if you for some reason have a [for](ref_keyword_for.asp) loop with no content, put in the [pass](ref_keyword_pass.asp) statement to avoid getting an error.
  
### Example
   for x in [0, 1, 2]:
 pass  [Try it Yourself »](trypython.asp?filename=demo_for_pass)    
## Exercise?
What will be the result of the following code:
for x in range(3):
 print(x)

0
1
20
1
2
31
2
3
